<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-531-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 531 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  June 18 1990 n3165 p178(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The next frontier is the text frontier; new programs help get thegold out of mountains of words. (information retrieval)(includesrelated article on hypertext)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Verity, John W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Research is increasing on full-text retrieval software that willallow users to search through masses of textual material andselect paragraphs, passages, or whole documents that includespecific words or phrases.andP;  Such software will provide crucial aidin the mission of organizing business paperwork and will helpresearchers who are developing computers that understand humanspeech.andP;  In 1990, the market for early versions of text retrievalsoftware is $98 million but it is expected to grow to $261 millionby 1993.andP;  Text retrieval software will allow companies to collectinformation without having to decide how to organize or search ituntil they need to use it.andP;  Information Dimensions Inc's Basissoftware is a leading text retrieval program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Text Data BasesComputer industryResearch and DevelopmentSoftware packagesSoftware DesignFuture of ComputingInformation Processing.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   U.S. sales of full-text retrieval software. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>